article.headline: Rockers find motivation despite tough year
article.linkText: Rockers find enough at end to slip past Shock
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- In a battle between the worst teams in the Eastern Conference, the Cleveland Rockers found a little extra at the end. Chasity Melvin scored 20 points and Merlakia Jones added 19 as Cleveland beat the Detroit Shock 68-66. "This is a really tough time for us, because it has been a bad season and we've got some players hurt,'' Melvin said. "It is hard to get up for games when you know they don't mean anything, but you have to finish the season as strong as you can.'' Cleveland (10-16) won its second in a row, while Detroit (6-20) lost for the second time in a row. The Shock were eliminated from playoff contention with the loss and Orlando's win over Charlotte. "We played hard, but they were able to pound the ball inside, and we didn't stop it,'' Shock coach Bill Laimbeer said. "Offensively, we just didn't attack the basket. They played zone and slowed the game down, but we still have to attack. We aren't a good enough perimeter team to stay outside.'' Ex-Shock player Jen Rizzotti added 11 points for Cleveland, while Mery Andrade had 10. Rookie Swin Cash led Detroit with 19 points, and Barb Farris had 12. Cleveland led 26-24 at the half behind eight points from Melvin, and after Detroit tied the game at 30 early in the second half, the Rockers went on an 10-0 run. But Detroit came back to tie the game at 45 on Dominique Canty's layup with 10:52 left. That was as close as it got. Cleveland responded with an 8-2 run that the Rockers up 53-47 with 8:29 left. Melvin and Jones had three points each in the surge. "Give Detroit credit -- they have a great young team and they fought us hard,'' Jones said. "This is a good win on the road.'' The Shock pulled within one on 3-pointers by Stacy Clinesmith and Elaine Powell, then took a 63-62 lead on Astou Ndiaye-Diatta's hook with 2:21 left. Melvin's three-point play put Cleveland back in front, and after Clinesmith missed, Jones moved the margin to four with a jumper. Cash answered with a three-pointer, and Cleveland turned the ball over, giving Detroit a chance to retake the lead. The Rockers triple-teamed Cash, who had to pass off to Farris, who missed as the shot clock expired. Jones split two free throws to make it 68-66 with four seconds left, and Powell dropped the ensuing inbounds pass. "It was an even game, but we were able to make the plays at the end -- both offensively and defensively,'' Rockers coach Dan Hughes said. "I'm proud of my team for that.''

Notes: Shock reserve Lenae Williams missed the game with a sprained ankle while Rockers forward Penny Taylor sat out with back pain. ... Detroit didn't get a point from a guard until Deanna Nolan's jumper to open the second half. ... The teams play again Saturday in Cleveland. ... Detroit tied a team record with nine blocks, led by four from Ayana Walker.
